/* ============================================================================
   linux+ :: content/domain3.js
   Lazy-loaded textbook reading module for XK0-006 Domain 3 (Security).
   Populates LINUXPLUS.reading[3]. Loaded on demand by app.js.
   ============================================================================ */
window.LINUXPLUS = window.LINUXPLUS || {}; LINUXPLUS.reading = LINUXPLUS.reading || {};
LINUXPLUS.reading[3] = [];
LINUXPLUS.reading[3].push(
  {heading:"Authentication, Authorization, and Accounting on Linux", body:"<p>Security on Linux is organized around a three-part model known as <span class='keyterm'>AAA</span>: authentication, authorization, and accounting. Mastering where each of these lives on a Linux host is the foundation for every other security topic on the exam, because firewalls, SELinux, sudo, and logging are all specific expressions of one of these three pillars.</p><h3>The Three A's Defined</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Authentication</span> answers the question <em>who are you?</em> -- it verifies an identity by checking a credential such as a password, an SSH key, a smart card, or a Kerberos ticket. <span class='keyterm'>Authorization</span> answers <em>what are you allowed to do?</em> -- once identity is proven, the system consults permissions, group membership, sudo rules, ACLs, and mandatory access control policy to decide whether an action is permitted. <span class='keyterm'>Accounting</span> answers <em>what did you do?</em> -- it records actions to logs and audit trails so that activity can be reviewed, billed, or investigated after the fact.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Pillar</th><th>Question</th><th>Linux mechanisms</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Authentication</td><td>Who are you?</td><td>PAM, <code>/etc/passwd</code>, <code>/etc/shadow</code>, SSH keys, Kerberos</td></tr><tr><td>Authorization</td><td>What may you do?</td><td>File permissions, sudo, ACLs, SELinux/AppArmor, Polkit</td></tr><tr><td>Accounting</td><td>What did you do?</td><td>journald, rsyslog, auditd, <code>/var/log/wtmp</code>, <code>last</code></td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Local Versus Centralized Authentication</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Local authentication</span> stores accounts in flat files on each host: <code>/etc/passwd</code> lists users and their UID, GID, home directory, and shell, while the hashed passwords live in the root-only <code>/etc/shadow</code>. This is simple and works offline, but it does not scale -- every change must be replicated to every machine. <span class='keyterm'>Centralized authentication</span> instead points all hosts at a shared directory such as LDAP or Active Directory, usually through <span class='keyterm'>SSSD</span> (System Security Services Daemon). One account change then applies fleet-wide, and password policy is enforced in a single place.</p><h3>Polkit: Fine-Grained Authorization</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Polkit</span> (formerly PolicyKit) is a framework that lets unprivileged processes ask a privileged daemon to perform specific actions without granting full root. When you insert a USB drive in a desktop session and it mounts without a password, or when <code>systemctl</code> prompts you to authenticate, Polkit is making the decision. Policies are defined as <code>.policy</code> XML files under <code>/usr/share/polkit-1/actions/</code> and overridden by rules in <code>/etc/polkit-1/rules.d/</code>. You inspect what an action requires with <code>pkaction --action-id org.freedesktop.systemd1.manage-units --verbose</code> and run a command as another user with <code>pkexec</code>, the Polkit equivalent of sudo. Polkit decisions hinge on whether a session is <em>active</em> and <em>local</em>, which is why a remote SSH session is often denied an action that a local console session is granted.</p><h3>Accounting Through Logs</h3><p>The accounting pillar is realized through the logging subsystem. Login records are written to the binary files <code>/var/log/wtmp</code> (logins and logouts), <code>/var/log/btmp</code> (failed logins), and <code>/var/run/utmp</code> (current sessions), read with <code>last</code>, <code>lastb</code>, and <code>who</code> respectively. The <code>lastlog</code> command shows the most recent login per account. Authentication events are funneled into <code>/var/log/auth.log</code> (Debian) or <code>/var/log/secure</code> (Red Hat). The audit daemon captures syscall-level accounting for compliance.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Record file</th><th>Read with</th><th>Contents</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>/var/log/wtmp</code></td><td><code>last</code></td><td>Successful logins and logouts, reboots</td></tr><tr><td><code>/var/log/btmp</code></td><td><code>lastb</code></td><td>Failed login attempts (root only)</td></tr><tr><td><code>/var/run/utmp</code></td><td><code>who</code> / <code>w</code></td><td>Sessions logged in right now</td></tr><tr><td><code>/var/log/lastlog</code></td><td><code>lastlog</code></td><td>Most recent login per account</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Identity Stores and NSS</h3><p>Whenever a name must be resolved to a UID, a group, or a host, the C library consults the <span class='keyterm'>Name Service Switch (NSS)</span>, configured in <code>/etc/nsswitch.conf</code>. A line such as <code>passwd: files sss</code> tells the system to look first in local <code>/etc/passwd</code> and then fall through to SSSD for directory accounts. This is the seam where local and centralized identity meet: authentication (proving the credential) runs through PAM, while identity resolution (turning <code>alice</code> into UID 1001 and her group list) runs through NSS. The command <code>getent passwd alice</code> exercises the full NSS chain and is the canonical way to confirm a directory account is visible to the host without attempting a login.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Concern</th><th>Subsystem</th><th>Config / probe</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Verify a credential</td><td>PAM</td><td><code>/etc/pam.d/</code>, login attempt</td></tr><tr><td>Resolve names to IDs</td><td>NSS</td><td><code>/etc/nsswitch.conf</code>, <code>getent</code></td></tr><tr><td>Decide an action</td><td>Polkit / sudo / DAC</td><td><code>pkaction</code>, <code>sudo -l</code></td></tr><tr><td>Record what happened</td><td>journald / auditd</td><td><code>journalctl</code>, <code>ausearch</code></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Keeping these layers distinct prevents a common troubleshooting trap: when <code>id alice</code> fails but the password was accepted, the problem is NSS resolution, not PAM authentication, and the fix is in <code>nsswitch.conf</code> or SSSD, never in the password itself.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>When a question describes a USB mount or service control that succeeds at the console but fails over SSH, the answer is <strong>Polkit</strong> -- it distinguishes active local sessions from remote ones. Do not confuse Polkit (authorization for system actions) with PAM (authentication during login), or with NSS, which only maps names to IDs.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[3].push(
  {heading:"PAM: Pluggable Authentication Modules", body:"<p><span class='keyterm'>PAM</span> (Pluggable Authentication Modules) is the framework that decouples applications from the mechanics of authentication. Instead of <code>login</code>, <code>sshd</code>, <code>sudo</code>, and <code>su</code> each hard-coding how to check a password, they call into PAM, and PAM consults a stack of pluggable modules. This is why adding multi-factor authentication or a password-complexity rule to a Linux host changes one config file rather than recompiling every program.</p><h3>The /etc/pam.d Directory</h3><p>Each PAM-aware service has a file under <code>/etc/pam.d/</code> named after the service: <code>/etc/pam.d/sshd</code>, <code>/etc/pam.d/sudo</code>, <code>/etc/pam.d/login</code>. Common rules are factored into shared files such as <code>system-auth</code> and <code>password-auth</code> (Red Hat) or <code>common-auth</code>, <code>common-password</code> (Debian), pulled in with an <code>include</code> line. A PAM line has four fields: the <em>type</em>, the <em>control flag</em>, the <em>module</em>, and optional <em>arguments</em>.</p><h3>The Four Module Types</h3><table><thead><tr><th>Type</th><th>Responsibility</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>auth</code></td><td>Verify the credential (prompt for and check the password or key)</td></tr><tr><td><code>account</code></td><td>Verify the account is valid (not expired, not locked, time-of-day rules)</td></tr><tr><td><code>password</code></td><td>Govern changing the credential (complexity, history, hashing)</td></tr><tr><td><code>session</code></td><td>Set up and tear down the session (mount home, set limits, log)</td></tr></tbody></table><p>Order matters absolutely: PAM evaluates each type's stack top to bottom, so a <code>sufficient</code> module that succeeds can short-circuit modules listed below it. An MFA line placed <em>after</em> a <code>sufficient</code> password module would never run -- a frequent configuration bug.</p><h3>Control Flags</h3><p>The control flag decides how each module's success or failure affects the overall result. <code>required</code> must succeed, but the rest of the stack still runs (so the failure reason is not leaked). <code>requisite</code> is like required but fails immediately. <code>sufficient</code> short-circuits with success if it passes and nothing required has already failed. <code>optional</code> matters only if it is the sole module. The newer syntax uses bracketed <code>[success=done default=ignore]</code> expressions for precise control.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Control flag</th><th>On success</th><th>On failure</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>required</code></td><td>Continue stack</td><td>Fail, but continue (hide reason)</td></tr><tr><td><code>requisite</code></td><td>Continue stack</td><td>Fail immediately, stop</td></tr><tr><td><code>sufficient</code></td><td>Succeed now (if no prior required failed)</td><td>Ignore, continue</td></tr><tr><td><code>optional</code></td><td>Continue</td><td>Ignored unless it is the only module</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Account Lockout: faillock and pam_tally2</h3><p>To defend against brute-force attacks, PAM can lock an account after repeated failures. The legacy module was <span class='keyterm'>pam_tally2</span>; it has been replaced on modern systems by <span class='keyterm'>pam_faillock</span>. A typical configuration locks an account for 15 minutes after 3 failures:</p><p><code>auth required pam_faillock.so preauth silent deny=3 unlock_time=900</code></p><p>You inspect and reset counters with the <code>faillock</code> command: <code>faillock --user alice</code> shows the failure record, and <code>faillock --user alice --reset</code> clears it so the user can log in again.</p><h3>Password Quality: pam_pwquality</h3><p>The <span class='keyterm'>pam_pwquality</span> module (configured in <code>/etc/security/pwquality.conf</code>) enforces complexity when a password is set. Key directives include <code>minlen=12</code> (minimum length), <code>dcredit</code>, <code>ucredit</code>, <code>lcredit</code>, and <code>ocredit</code> (credits for digits, uppercase, lowercase, and other characters), <code>minclass=3</code> (require characters from at least three classes), and <code>retry=3</code>. A negative credit such as <code>dcredit=-1</code> means at least one digit is mandatory rather than merely earning length credit.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Directive</th><th>Meaning</th><th>Example</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>minlen</code></td><td>Minimum length (after credits)</td><td><code>minlen=14</code></td></tr><tr><td><code>minclass</code></td><td>Distinct character classes required</td><td><code>minclass=3</code></td></tr><tr><td><code>dcredit / ucredit</code></td><td>Digit / uppercase credit (negative = require)</td><td><code>dcredit=-1</code></td></tr><tr><td><code>retry</code></td><td>Attempts before giving up</td><td><code>retry=3</code></td></tr><tr><td><code>difok</code></td><td>Characters that must differ from old password</td><td><code>difok=5</code></td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Why the Order of auth Lines Matters</h3><p>A correct <code>pam_faillock</code> deployment uses two lines: a <code>preauth</code> line before the password module that checks whether the account is already locked, and an <code>authfail</code> line after it that increments the counter on a failed attempt. Omit the <code>authfail</code> line and failures are never counted; place the <code>preauth</code> line in the wrong order and a locked account can still attempt a login. Because these subtleties are easy to get wrong, Red Hat ships <code>authselect</code> to generate validated stacks rather than hand-editing <code>system-auth</code>.</p><p>A few session-type modules round out a real stack and appear regularly on the exam. <code>pam_limits</code> enforces the resource ceilings in <code>/etc/security/limits.conf</code> (maximum open files, processes, locked memory) at login. <code>pam_env</code> sets environment variables from <code>/etc/security/pam_env.conf</code>. <code>pam_mkhomedir</code> creates a home directory on first login, which is essential for directory-based accounts that have no pre-made home. <code>pam_time</code> restricts logins to allowed hours, and <code>pam_nologin</code> blocks non-root logins whenever <code>/etc/nologin</code> exists -- the mechanism that keeps users out during maintenance. Knowing which type each belongs to (mostly <code>session</code>, with <code>pam_time</code> and <code>pam_nologin</code> under <code>account</code>) is exactly the kind of mapping a question will test.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>A user reports being locked out after fat-fingering their password three times. As root you run <code>faillock --user bob</code> to confirm the lock, then <code>faillock --user bob --reset</code> to clear it -- no password change is required, and you never edit <code>/etc/shadow</code> directly to fix this.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[3].push(
  {heading:"Centralized Identity: LDAP, Kerberos, SSSD, and Samba", body:"<p>Managing local accounts on dozens or thousands of servers is unmanageable, so enterprises centralize identity in a directory service and have every host consult it. The Linux+ exam expects you to know the four building blocks of centralized identity and how they fit together.</p><h3>LDAP: The Directory</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>LDAP</span> (Lightweight Directory Access Protocol) is a protocol for querying a hierarchical directory of objects -- users, groups, hosts -- organized as a tree of entries identified by a <span class='keyterm'>distinguished name (DN)</span> such as <code>uid=alice,ou=People,dc=example,dc=com</code>. LDAP listens on TCP 389 (plaintext or StartTLS) and 636 (LDAPS over TLS). You query it with <code>ldapsearch</code>: <code>ldapsearch -x -H ldap://dir.example.com -b dc=example,dc=com '(uid=alice)'</code>. Used alone, LDAP can authenticate by performing a <em>bind</em> with the user's DN and password, but binding the password over the wire makes TLS essential.</p><h3>Kerberos: The Ticket System</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Kerberos</span> solves authentication without sending passwords across the network. A user authenticates once to the <span class='keyterm'>KDC</span> (Key Distribution Center) and receives a <span class='keyterm'>TGT</span> (Ticket-Granting Ticket); to access a service, the client presents the TGT and receives a service ticket. Because tickets are time-stamped and encrypted, Kerberos requires that clocks be tightly synchronized (typically within five minutes), which is why NTP is a hard dependency. You obtain a ticket with <code>kinit alice@EXAMPLE.COM</code>, list cached tickets with <code>klist</code>, and discard them with <code>kdestroy</code>. Realms are written in uppercase by convention.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Component</th><th>Role</th><th>Default port</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>LDAP / LDAPS</td><td>Stores identities and attributes</td><td>389 / 636</td></tr><tr><td>Kerberos KDC</td><td>Issues authentication tickets</td><td>88</td></tr><tr><td>kpasswd</td><td>Kerberos password changes</td><td>464</td></tr><tr><td>SSSD</td><td>Client-side connector and cache</td><td>n/a (local daemon)</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>SSSD: The Connector and Cache</h3><p>In practice you rarely wire LDAP and Kerberos into PAM and NSS directly. Instead <span class='keyterm'>SSSD</span> (System Security Services Daemon) sits between the host and the directory. SSSD authenticates via Kerberos, pulls identity attributes via LDAP, and -- crucially -- <em>caches</em> credentials so that a laptop can still log in offline. It integrates with PAM (for authentication) and NSS (for resolving usernames and groups), configured in <code>/etc/sssd/sssd.conf</code>, which must be mode <code>0600</code> or the daemon refuses to start. The <code>sss_cache</code> command invalidates cached entries.</p><h3>Samba and Active Directory</h3><p>Most enterprises run <span class='keyterm'>Active Directory</span>, which is essentially LDAP plus Kerberos plus DNS in one Microsoft package. A Linux host joins AD either with <code>realm join example.com</code> (which configures SSSD automatically) or with Samba's <code>net ads join</code>. <span class='keyterm'>Samba</span> also implements the SMB/CIFS protocol so Linux can share files with and consume shares from Windows; its configuration lives in <code>/etc/samba/smb.conf</code> and the daemons are <code>smbd</code> and <code>nmbd</code>. After joining, <code>id alice@example.com</code> should resolve a domain user, confirming integration works end to end.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Task</th><th>Command</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Discover a realm</td><td><code>realm discover example.com</code></td></tr><tr><td>Join Active Directory</td><td><code>realm join -U admin example.com</code></td></tr><tr><td>List joined realms</td><td><code>realm list</code></td></tr><tr><td>Restrict who may log in</td><td><code>realm permit -g sysadmins@example.com</code></td></tr><tr><td>Invalidate SSSD cache</td><td><code>sss_cache -E</code></td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Troubleshooting the Join</h3><p>When a domain login fails, work the layers in order. First confirm DNS resolves the SRV records the KDC and LDAP servers advertise -- <code>dig -t SRV _ldap._tcp.example.com</code> -- because AD relies entirely on DNS for service discovery. Next confirm time sync with <code>chronyc tracking</code>; Kerberos rejects tickets when drift exceeds the default five-minute window. Then verify a ticket can be obtained at all with <code>kinit alice@EXAMPLE.COM</code> followed by <code>klist</code>. Only after those pass should you inspect <code>/etc/sssd/sssd.conf</code> and the SSSD logs under <code>/var/log/sssd/</code>. Remember the file-mode gotcha: SSSD refuses to start if <code>sssd.conf</code> is anything but <code>0600</code>, and the daemon fails silently in some distributions.</p><p>It also helps to know how the pieces map onto the older, manual stack that SSSD replaced. Before SSSD, a host wired LDAP into name resolution through <code>nss_ldap</code> and into login through <code>pam_ldap</code>, with Kerberos handled separately by <code>pam_krb5</code> -- three modules, three configs, and no offline cache. SSSD folds all of that into one daemon with a single cache, which is why a laptop that authenticated against the directory yesterday can still log in on a plane today. Each directory it talks to is a <em>domain</em> block in <code>sssd.conf</code> with an <code>id_provider</code> (usually <code>ldap</code> or <code>ad</code>) and an <code>auth_provider</code> (often <code>krb5</code>), making the separation of identity lookup from credential verification explicit in the configuration itself.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>If logins to a domain-joined host suddenly fail with ticket errors, suspect <strong>clock skew</strong> first -- Kerberos rejects tickets when the client and KDC clocks drift beyond the allowed window. Verify and fix time synchronization before touching SSSD or LDAP config.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[3].push(
  {heading:"Logging and the Audit Daemon", body:"<p>Accounting -- the third A of AAA -- depends on reliable logging. Modern Linux runs two complementary systems: the structured, binary <span class='keyterm'>systemd journal</span> and the traditional text-based <span class='keyterm'>rsyslog</span>. For security and compliance there is also the kernel <span class='keyterm'>audit</span> subsystem. Knowing how to query and forward logs is core exam material.</p><h3>journald and journalctl</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>journald</span> collects log data into an indexed binary store queried with <code>journalctl</code>. Useful invocations include <code>journalctl -u sshd</code> (one unit), <code>journalctl -b</code> (current boot), <code>journalctl -p err</code> (priority error and worse), <code>journalctl --since '1 hour ago'</code>, and <code>journalctl -f</code> (follow live). By default the journal is volatile and cleared on reboot; to persist it, create <code>/var/log/journal/</code> and the journal survives reboots, after which <code>journalctl --list-boots</code> and <code>journalctl -b -1</code> let you read the previous boot.</p><h3>rsyslog: Facilities and Severities</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>rsyslog</span> writes plain-text logs and is still essential for forwarding to a central server. Its rules in <code>/etc/rsyslog.conf</code> and <code>/etc/rsyslog.d/*.conf</code> match a <em>facility</em> (the source subsystem) and a <em>severity</em> (the urgency), then specify a destination. The classic syntax <code>authpriv.* /var/log/secure</code> sends all authentication messages to that file.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Facilities</th><th>Severities (high to low)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>auth, authpriv, cron, daemon, kern, mail, user, local0-local7</td><td>emerg, alert, crit, err, warning, notice, info, debug</td></tr></tbody></table><p>To forward logs to a central collector, add <code>*.* @@logserver.example.com:514</code> -- a single <code>@</code> means UDP, a double <code>@@</code> means TCP. Centralized logging is a security control because an attacker who compromises a host cannot erase logs that already left it.</p><h3>logrotate</h3><p>Without rotation, logs grow until they fill <code>/var</code>. <span class='keyterm'>logrotate</span>, driven by <code>/etc/logrotate.conf</code> and per-service files in <code>/etc/logrotate.d/</code>, compresses, renames, and prunes old logs. Directives include <code>weekly</code>, <code>rotate 4</code> (keep four old copies), <code>compress</code>, <code>missingok</code>, and a <code>postrotate</code> script to signal the daemon to reopen its file. Test a config without waiting for cron using <code>logrotate -d /etc/logrotate.conf</code> (debug) or force a run with <code>logrotate -f</code>.</p><h3>The /var/log Layout</h3><p>Key files are <code>/var/log/messages</code> or <code>/var/log/syslog</code> (general), <code>/var/log/secure</code> or <code>/var/log/auth.log</code> (authentication), <code>/var/log/cron</code>, <code>/var/log/maillog</code>, <code>/var/log/boot.log</code>, and the kernel ring buffer via <code>dmesg</code>.</p><h3>The Audit Daemon: auditd</h3><p>For regulatory compliance the kernel <span class='keyterm'>audit</span> subsystem records security-relevant events with attribution. The <code>auditd</code> daemon writes to <code>/var/log/audit/audit.log</code>. You add rules at runtime with <code>auditctl</code> and persist them in <code>/etc/audit/rules.d/</code>. For example, <code>auditctl -w /etc/passwd -p wa -k passwd_changes</code> watches that file for write and attribute changes, tagging events with the key <code>passwd_changes</code>. You then query with <code>ausearch -k passwd_changes</code> and summarize with <code>aureport --summary</code>. SELinux denials also land in the audit log, which is why audit and SELinux troubleshooting overlap.</p><table><thead><tr><th>journalctl flag</th><th>Shows</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>-u sshd</code></td><td>Logs for one systemd unit</td></tr><tr><td><code>-b</code> / <code>-b -1</code></td><td>Current boot / previous boot</td></tr><tr><td><code>-p err</code></td><td>Priority error and worse</td></tr><tr><td><code>--since / --until</code></td><td>Time window (e.g. '1 hour ago')</td></tr><tr><td><code>-f</code></td><td>Follow new entries live</td></tr><tr><td><code>--disk-usage</code></td><td>How much space the journal consumes</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Capping Journal Size</h3><p>A persistent journal can fill <code>/var</code> if uncapped. The limits live in <code>/etc/systemd/journald.conf</code>: <code>SystemMaxUse=500M</code> bounds total size, <code>MaxRetentionSec=1month</code> ages out old entries, and <code>Storage=persistent</code> forces on-disk retention. You can vacuum on demand with <code>journalctl --vacuum-size=200M</code> or <code>journalctl --vacuum-time=2weeks</code>, which is the immediate fix when a disk-full alert points at the journal. Where rsyslog and journald coexist, <code>journald</code> typically forwards to <code>rsyslog</code> via the <code>imuxsock</code>/<code>imjournal</code> input so the same events appear both as structured journal records and as plain-text files.</p><p>For audit rules, distinguish the two kinds you can write. A <em>file watch</em> like <code>auditctl -w /etc/shadow -p wa -k shadow</code> alerts on write or attribute changes to a path. A <em>syscall rule</em> like <code>auditctl -a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S execve -k exec</code> traps every invocation of a system call, which is how you log all program executions or all uses of a privileged syscall. Rules added with <code>auditctl</code> are runtime-only; to persist them you place the same lines in a file under <code>/etc/audit/rules.d/</code> and let <code>augenrules</code> compile them at boot. Because the audit log can itself be a target for tampering, pairing it with the append-only <code>chattr +a</code> attribute and remote forwarding is a common hardening requirement.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Severity</th><th>Numeric</th><th>Use</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>emerg</code> / <code>alert</code> / <code>crit</code></td><td>0 / 1 / 2</td><td>System unusable / act now / critical</td></tr><tr><td><code>err</code> / <code>warning</code></td><td>3 / 4</td><td>Errors and warnings</td></tr><tr><td><code>notice</code> / <code>info</code> / <code>debug</code></td><td>5 / 6 / 7</td><td>Normal, informational, verbose</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>Remember the forwarding syntax: <code>@host</code> is UDP, <code>@@host</code> is TCP. For audit questions, the trio is <strong>auditctl</strong> (define rules), <strong>ausearch</strong> (query by key), and <strong>aureport</strong> (summarize). The <code>-k</code> key is how you tie a rule to its search.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[3].push(
  {heading:"Firewalls I: firewalld and Zones", body:"<p>A host firewall filters traffic at the kernel using Netfilter, but administrators interact with it through a higher-level manager. On the Red Hat family the default manager is <span class='keyterm'>firewalld</span>, a dynamic daemon that organizes rules into <span class='keyterm'>zones</span>. Understanding zones and the <code>firewall-cmd</code> workflow is heavily tested.</p><h3>The Zone Model</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>zone</span> is a named trust level. Each network interface is assigned to a zone, and the zone's ruleset decides what is allowed. This lets a multi-homed host treat its internal NIC liberally and its internet-facing NIC strictly. The default zone for unclassified interfaces is usually <code>public</code>.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Zone</th><th>Trust level / typical use</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>drop</code></td><td>Drop all incoming, no reply (most hostile)</td></tr><tr><td><code>block</code></td><td>Reject incoming with an ICMP error</td></tr><tr><td><code>public</code></td><td>Untrusted networks; default for new interfaces</td></tr><tr><td><code>home</code> / <code>internal</code></td><td>Mostly trusted home or internal LAN</td></tr><tr><td><code>trusted</code></td><td>Allow all traffic (most permissive)</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>The firewall-cmd Workflow</h3><p>The critical concept is the split between the <em>runtime</em> configuration (active now, lost on reload) and the <em>permanent</em> configuration (on disk, applied on reload). A change made without <code>--permanent</code> takes effect immediately but vanishes on reload; a change made with <code>--permanent</code> persists but does not take effect until you reload. The disciplined pattern is to apply permanently and then reload:</p><p><code>firewall-cmd --permanent --add-service=https</code><br><code>firewall-cmd --reload</code></p><p>Other essential commands include <code>firewall-cmd --state</code>, <code>firewall-cmd --get-active-zones</code>, <code>firewall-cmd --list-all</code> (everything in the default zone), <code>firewall-cmd --permanent --add-port=8080/tcp</code>, and assigning an interface with <code>firewall-cmd --permanent --zone=internal --change-interface=eth1</code>. Use <code>firewall-cmd --runtime-to-permanent</code> to save accumulated runtime tweaks once you are satisfied they work.</p><h3>Services Versus Ports</h3><p>firewalld ships named <span class='keyterm'>services</span> -- predefined bundles of ports and protocols stored as XML in <code>/usr/lib/firewalld/services/</code>. Opening <code>--add-service=ssh</code> is clearer and more maintainable than <code>--add-port=22/tcp</code> because it documents intent. List available services with <code>firewall-cmd --get-services</code>.</p><h3>Rich Rules</h3><p>When you need conditions beyond a simple allow -- source-address restrictions, logging, rate limiting, or per-source actions -- you use <span class='keyterm'>rich rules</span>. For example, to allow SSH only from one subnet:</p><p><code>firewall-cmd --permanent --add-rich-rule='rule family=\"ipv4\" source address=\"10.0.0.0/24\" service name=\"ssh\" accept'</code></p><p>Rich rules can also drop or reject specific sources, log matches at a chosen rate, and combine source plus port plus action in a single expression, giving firewalld much of the power of raw nftables while keeping the zone abstraction.</p><table><thead><tr><th>firewall-cmd command</th><th>Purpose</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>--state</code></td><td>Is firewalld running?</td></tr><tr><td><code>--get-default-zone</code></td><td>Show the default zone</td></tr><tr><td><code>--set-default-zone=home</code></td><td>Change the default zone</td></tr><tr><td><code>--get-active-zones</code></td><td>Zones with bound interfaces/sources</td></tr><tr><td><code>--list-all</code></td><td>Everything in the active zone</td></tr><tr><td><code>--runtime-to-permanent</code></td><td>Persist accumulated runtime rules</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Binding by Source Versus Interface</h3><p>A zone can be bound to an interface (<code>--change-interface=eth1</code>) or to a source address (<code>--add-source=10.0.0.0/24</code>). Source bindings win over interface bindings, so a packet from a source explicitly assigned to <code>trusted</code> is handled there even if it arrived on an interface bound to <code>public</code>. Misunderstanding that precedence is a classic reason a rule seems to be ignored. To see exactly where a packet would land, <code>firewall-cmd --get-zone-of-interface=eth0</code> and <code>firewall-cmd --get-zone-of-source=10.0.0.5</code> resolve the bindings directly.</p><h3>Panic Mode and Reloading</h3><p>For an emergency cut-off, <code>firewall-cmd --panic-on</code> drops all traffic instantly; <code>--panic-off</code> restores. Distinguish <code>--reload</code> (apply the permanent config, keeping established connections) from <code>--complete-reload</code> (a harder reset that drops conntrack state and is rarely needed). On the wire, firewalld now uses the nftables backend by default, so its rules show up under <code>nft list ruleset</code> -- useful when you want to confirm what a high-level rule actually generated.</p><p>A subtle but frequently tested behavior is that firewalld is <em>dynamic</em>: unlike a static iptables script, it can add or change a rule without flushing and rebuilding the entire ruleset, so existing connections are not torn down on every edit. This is the headline advantage over the older <code>iptables</code> service, where any change meant reloading the whole table. Permanent definitions are stored as XML under <code>/etc/firewalld/zones/</code>, so they can be version-controlled and copied between hosts. When you assign an interface to a zone, the binding is also written into the matching NetworkManager connection profile, which is why a zone can appear to reset after a network restart if the two disagree -- always confirm with <code>nmcli connection show</code> when a zone assignment will not stick across reboots.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>The single most common firewalld mistake on the exam is forgetting that <code>--permanent</code> changes need a <code>firewall-cmd --reload</code> to become active, and that runtime changes disappear on reload. If a question says a rule was added permanently but is not yet working, the answer is <strong>reload the firewall</strong>.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[3].push(
  {heading:"Firewalls II: iptables, nftables, and ufw", body:"<p>Underneath every Linux firewall manager sits the kernel's <span class='keyterm'>Netfilter</span> framework. firewalld and ufw are front ends; the rules themselves are expressed through <span class='keyterm'>iptables</span> (legacy) or its successor <span class='keyterm'>nftables</span>. The exam expects fluency in the iptables model and awareness of where ufw and ipset fit.</p><h3>The iptables Model: Tables, Chains, Targets</h3><p>iptables organizes rules into <span class='keyterm'>tables</span>, each containing <span class='keyterm'>chains</span> of rules, each ending in a <span class='keyterm'>target</span>. The <code>filter</code> table (the default) decides whether to allow traffic; the <code>nat</code> table rewrites addresses; the <code>mangle</code> table alters packet headers. Within the filter table the built-in chains are <code>INPUT</code> (to this host), <code>OUTPUT</code> (from this host), and <code>FORWARD</code> (routed through this host).</p><table><thead><tr><th>Target</th><th>Action</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>ACCEPT</code></td><td>Allow the packet</td></tr><tr><td><code>DROP</code></td><td>Silently discard (no reply to sender)</td></tr><tr><td><code>REJECT</code></td><td>Discard and send an ICMP error back</td></tr><tr><td><code>LOG</code></td><td>Log and continue evaluating</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Stateful Versus Stateless</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>stateless</span> firewall judges each packet in isolation. A <span class='keyterm'>stateful</span> firewall tracks connections via the <code>conntrack</code> module, so it can allow return traffic for connections it already permitted. The canonical stateful rule is <code>iptables -A INPUT -m state --state ESTABLISHED,RELATED -j ACCEPT</code>, which lets replies in without opening every port. A working ruleset typically reads: accept loopback, accept established/related, accept specific new services, then set the default policy to drop with <code>iptables -P INPUT DROP</code>.</p><h3>Example iptables Commands</h3><p><code>iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 22 -j ACCEPT</code> appends an SSH-allow rule. <code>iptables -L -n -v --line-numbers</code> lists rules with counters. <code>iptables -D INPUT 3</code> deletes rule number three. Because iptables rules are not persistent by default, you save them with <code>iptables-save &gt; /etc/iptables/rules.v4</code> and restore with <code>iptables-restore</code>.</p><h3>nftables: The Successor</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>nftables</span> replaces iptables, ip6tables, arptables, and ebtables with one tool, <code>nft</code>, and one unified syntax. Rules live in a single ruleset of tables and chains defined in <code>/etc/nftables.conf</code>. You list everything with <code>nft list ruleset</code> and add a rule with <code>nft add rule inet filter input tcp dport 22 accept</code>. nftables is faster, supports atomic ruleset replacement, and is the modern default; firewalld itself now uses the nftables backend.</p><h3>ufw: The Simple Front End</h3><p>On Ubuntu and Debian, <span class='keyterm'>ufw</span> (Uncomplicated Firewall) provides a beginner-friendly interface over iptables/nftables. Commands are intuitive: <code>ufw enable</code>, <code>ufw allow 22/tcp</code>, <code>ufw allow OpenSSH</code>, <code>ufw deny 23</code>, <code>ufw status verbose</code>, and <code>ufw delete allow 80</code>. Set defaults with <code>ufw default deny incoming</code>.</p><h3>ipset</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>ipset</span> stores large collections of addresses in an efficient kernel hash so a single firewall rule can match thousands of IPs. You create a set with <code>ipset create blocklist hash:ip</code>, populate it with <code>ipset add blocklist 203.0.113.5</code>, and reference it from one iptables rule, which is far faster than thousands of individual rules -- the basis of many automated blocklisting tools.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Manager</th><th>Underlying engine</th><th>Default on</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>iptables</td><td>Netfilter (legacy / nft compat)</td><td>Older RHEL/Debian</td></tr><tr><td>nftables (<code>nft</code>)</td><td>Netfilter (native)</td><td>Modern distros</td></tr><tr><td>firewalld</td><td>nftables backend</td><td>RHEL/Fedora</td></tr><tr><td>ufw</td><td>iptables/nftables</td><td>Ubuntu</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>iptables Tables and Their Order</h3><p>When several tables apply to the same hook, they run in a fixed order: <code>raw</code> (connection-tracking exemptions), then <code>mangle</code> (header edits), then <code>nat</code> (address rewrites, only for the first packet of a flow), then <code>filter</code> (allow/deny). Knowing this order explains why a DNAT in <code>nat/PREROUTING</code> changes the destination <em>before</em> the routing decision and the <code>filter/FORWARD</code> check, so your forward rules must reference the post-translation address.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Table</th><th>Job</th><th>Common chains</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>filter</code></td><td>Allow / deny</td><td>INPUT, OUTPUT, FORWARD</td></tr><tr><td><code>nat</code></td><td>Rewrite addresses</td><td>PREROUTING, POSTROUTING</td></tr><tr><td><code>mangle</code></td><td>Alter headers (TTL, TOS)</td><td>All five hooks</td></tr><tr><td><code>raw</code></td><td>Skip conntrack</td><td>PREROUTING, OUTPUT</td></tr></tbody></table><p>Rule ordering within a chain is equally decisive because matching is first-match-wins: iptables walks the chain top to bottom and stops at the first rule whose target makes a terminal decision. A permissive rule placed above a restrictive one renders the restriction dead. This is why you <em>insert</em> a high-priority rule with <code>iptables -I INPUT 1 ...</code> rather than appending it, and why auditing with <code>iptables -L --line-numbers</code> is the first step before editing. Persistence differs by tool too: <code>iptables-save</code>/<code>iptables-restore</code> for raw iptables, the <code>netfilter-persistent</code> or <code>iptables-services</code> package on managed systems, and a simple <code>nft list ruleset &gt; /etc/nftables.conf</code> for nftables.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>You lock down a server with <code>iptables -P INPUT DROP</code> but first forget to accept established connections, and your SSH session freezes. The fix is always to add <code>iptables -A INPUT -m state --state ESTABLISHED,RELATED -j ACCEPT</code> and a loopback accept <em>before</em> setting a default-drop policy.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[3].push(
  {heading:"NAT and Packet Forwarding", body:"<p>When a Linux host routes traffic between networks -- as a gateway, a container host, or a VPN endpoint -- it must both <span class='keyterm'>forward</span> packets and often <span class='keyterm'>translate</span> their addresses. Network Address Translation (NAT) and IP forwarding are tightly linked, and the exam tests when each variant applies.</p><h3>Enabling IP Forwarding</h3><p>By default a Linux kernel drops packets not addressed to itself; it is a host, not a router. To make it forward, you enable the kernel tunable <code>net.ipv4.ip_forward</code>. Set it for the moment with <code>sysctl -w net.ipv4.ip_forward=1</code> (equivalently <code>echo 1 &gt; /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward</code>), and persist it across reboots by adding <code>net.ipv4.ip_forward = 1</code> to a file under <code>/etc/sysctl.d/</code> and running <code>sysctl --system</code>. Without this, no NAT rule will route anything.</p><h3>The Three Flavors of NAT</h3><table><thead><tr><th>Type</th><th>What it rewrites</th><th>Typical use</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><span class='keyterm'>SNAT</span></td><td>Source address (fixed IP)</td><td>Outbound from a LAN behind a known public IP</td></tr><tr><td><span class='keyterm'>Masquerade</span></td><td>Source address (dynamic IP / PAT)</td><td>Outbound when the public IP is assigned by DHCP</td></tr><tr><td><span class='keyterm'>DNAT</span></td><td>Destination address</td><td>Port forwarding inbound to an internal server</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>SNAT and Masquerade</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>SNAT</span> (Source NAT) rewrites the source address of outbound packets so that replies return to the gateway. Use it when the gateway has a static public IP:</p><p><code>iptables -t nat -A POSTROUTING -s 10.0.0.0/24 -o eth0 -j SNAT --to-source 203.0.113.10</code></p><p><span class='keyterm'>Masquerade</span> is a special form of SNAT that uses whatever address the outgoing interface currently has, which is essential when that address is dynamic (a home or cloud link):</p><p><code>iptables -t nat -A POSTROUTING -o eth0 -j MASQUERADE</code></p><p>Because many internal hosts share one external address, the gateway also rewrites source <em>ports</em> to keep flows distinct -- this is <span class='keyterm'>PAT</span> (Port Address Translation), often called NAT overload, and masquerade implements it automatically.</p><h3>DNAT and Port Forwarding</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>DNAT</span> (Destination NAT) rewrites the destination so external requests reach an internal server. To forward inbound web traffic to a backend host:</p><p><code>iptables -t nat -A PREROUTING -i eth0 -p tcp --dport 80 -j DNAT --to-destination 10.0.0.5:8080</code></p><p>Note the chains differ by direction: SNAT and masquerade happen in <code>POSTROUTING</code> (after the routing decision, as the packet leaves), while DNAT happens in <code>PREROUTING</code> (before routing, as the packet arrives). With firewalld the same is achieved with <code>firewall-cmd --permanent --add-masquerade</code> and <code>firewall-cmd --permanent --add-forward-port=port=80:proto=tcp:toport=8080:toaddr=10.0.0.5</code>.</p><h3>When to Use Each</h3><p>Use masquerade for typical internet sharing where the WAN IP changes; use SNAT when the public IP is fixed and you want slightly better performance and predictability; use DNAT to publish an internal service. All three require IP forwarding enabled and a permissive enough FORWARD chain to actually pass the routed packets.</p><table><thead><tr><th>NAT type</th><th>Chain</th><th>iptables target</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>SNAT</td><td>POSTROUTING</td><td><code>-j SNAT --to-source</code></td></tr><tr><td>Masquerade</td><td>POSTROUTING</td><td><code>-j MASQUERADE</code></td></tr><tr><td>DNAT</td><td>PREROUTING</td><td><code>-j DNAT --to-destination</code></td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Verifying the Path</h3><p>NAT failures are almost always one of three things: forwarding not enabled, the FORWARD policy dropping routed packets, or conntrack not seeing the return path. Confirm the kernel flag with <code>sysctl net.ipv4.ip_forward</code>, watch translations in real time with <code>conntrack -L -p tcp</code> or <code>cat /proc/net/nf_conntrack</code>, and verify the NAT rules and their hit counters with <code>iptables -t nat -L -n -v</code>. A rule with a zero packet counter that you expect to be matching tells you traffic is not even reaching that chain -- usually a routing or forwarding problem rather than a NAT-syntax problem.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Check</th><th>Command</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Forwarding enabled?</td><td><code>sysctl net.ipv4.ip_forward</code></td></tr><tr><td>NAT rule hit counts</td><td><code>iptables -t nat -L -n -v</code></td></tr><tr><td>Live translations</td><td><code>conntrack -L</code></td></tr><tr><td>firewalld masquerade on?</td><td><code>firewall-cmd --query-masquerade</code></td></tr></tbody></table><p>One more dependency catches people out: NAT translation only happens for the <em>first</em> packet of a connection, after which conntrack handles the rest of the flow automatically from the cached translation. This means a NAT rule appended after a connection is already established will not retroactively rewrite that flow -- you must clear the conntrack entry (or restart the connection) for a new rule to take effect. It also explains why <code>conntrack -L</code> is the authoritative view of what is actually being translated, more reliable than reading the rules alone. For IPv6, remember that masquerade and SNAT exist but are far less common because globally routable addresses make NAT largely unnecessary; the exam emphasis stays on IPv4 NAT with <code>net.ipv4.ip_forward</code>.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>Three facts to memorize: <strong>masquerade = dynamic source IP</strong>, <strong>SNAT = static source IP</strong>, <strong>DNAT = inbound port forwarding</strong>. And NAT does nothing unless <code>net.ipv4.ip_forward=1</code> is set -- a forgotten forwarding flag is the classic reason a correctly written NAT rule fails to route.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[3].push(
  {heading:"Privilege Escalation: su, sudo, and the sudoers File", body:"<p>Administrators rarely log in as root directly; instead they elevate from an unprivileged account when needed. The two mechanisms are <span class='keyterm'>su</span> and <span class='keyterm'>sudo</span>, and the difference between them -- and how sudo is configured -- is among the most heavily tested areas of the domain.</p><h3>su Versus su -</h3><p>The <code>su</code> command (substitute user) switches to another account, prompting for <em>that account's</em> password. The subtle but critical distinction is the dash: <code>su</code> keeps your current environment and working directory, while <code>su -</code> (or <code>su -l</code>) starts a <span class='keyterm'>login shell</span>, loading the target user's full environment -- their <code>PATH</code>, profile scripts, and home directory. Forgetting the dash is a classic cause of <em>command not found</em> errors after switching to root, because root's <code>/sbin</code> directories are not in a normal user's PATH.</p><h3>sudo: Per-Command Elevation</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>sudo</span> (superuser do) runs a single command with elevated privilege, but the user authenticates with <em>their own</em> password, not root's. This is auditable -- every sudo invocation is logged to <code>/var/log/secure</code> or <code>/var/log/auth.log</code> -- and far safer than sharing the root password. <code>sudo -i</code> opens an interactive root login shell; <code>sudo -u alice command</code> runs as another user; <code>sudo -l</code> lists what the current user is permitted.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Command</th><th>Effect</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>su</code></td><td>Switch to root, keep current environment (needs root password)</td></tr><tr><td><code>su -</code></td><td>Switch to root with a full login environment</td></tr><tr><td><code>sudo cmd</code></td><td>Run one command as root (needs your own password)</td></tr><tr><td><code>sudo -i</code></td><td>Open a root login shell via sudo</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>The sudoers File and visudo</h3><p>Permissions are defined in <code>/etc/sudoers</code> and drop-in files under <code>/etc/sudoers.d/</code>. You must <strong>never</strong> edit these with a plain text editor; always use <span class='keyterm'>visudo</span>, which locks the file and validates syntax before saving. A broken sudoers file can lock everyone out of root, and visudo's syntax check is the safeguard. A typical entry reads:</p><p><code>alice ALL=(ALL:ALL) ALL</code></p><p>The fields are: user, then <code>host=(runas_user:runas_group)</code>, then the allowed commands. To grant passwordless privilege you add the <code>NOPASSWD:</code> tag:</p><p><code>deploy ALL=(ALL) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/systemctl restart app</code></p><h3>NOPASSWD Implications</h3><p><code>NOPASSWD</code> is convenient for automation but dangerous: anyone who compromises that account, or any process running as it, gains the listed privileges with no further check. Scope it to the narrowest possible command list, and beware command paths that allow shell escapes (granting <code>NOPASSWD</code> on an editor or pager effectively grants a root shell).</p><h3>wheel and sudo Groups</h3><p>Rather than listing every admin individually, distributions delegate to a group: the <span class='keyterm'>wheel</span> group on Red Hat and the <span class='keyterm'>sudo</span> group on Debian/Ubuntu. The sudoers line <code>%wheel ALL=(ALL) ALL</code> (the <code>%</code> marks a group) grants all members admin rights, so adding a user with <code>usermod -aG wheel bob</code> is how you make someone an administrator.</p><table><thead><tr><th>sudoers element</th><th>Meaning</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>%wheel</code></td><td>Applies to members of group wheel</td></tr><tr><td><code>(ALL:ALL)</code></td><td>May run as any user and any group</td></tr><tr><td><code>NOPASSWD:</code></td><td>No password prompt for the listed commands</td></tr><tr><td><code>!/bin/su</code></td><td>Explicitly forbid a command</td></tr><tr><td><code>Defaults targetpw</code></td><td>Prompt for the target's password, not the caller's</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Drop-in Files and Aliases</h3><p>Modern practice avoids editing the monolithic <code>/etc/sudoers</code> and instead drops per-purpose files into <code>/etc/sudoers.d/</code>, each still edited through <code>visudo -f /etc/sudoers.d/deploy</code> so syntax is validated. Sudoers also supports aliases that make large policies readable: <code>User_Alias ADMINS = alice, bob</code>, <code>Cmnd_Alias SERVICES = /usr/bin/systemctl</code>, and <code>Host_Alias WEB = web1, web2</code>, combined as <code>ADMINS WEB = (root) SERVICES</code>. The <code>Defaults</code> line tunes behavior globally -- <code>Defaults logfile=/var/log/sudo.log</code>, <code>Defaults timestamp_timeout=5</code> (minutes the cached credential lasts), and <code>Defaults requiretty</code>. Because a single stray character can lock out all admins, the validating editor is non-negotiable; if you ever do break it, recovery is via a root shell or single-user mode.</p><p>Two security nuances make sudo more than a convenience. First, sudo logs the full command, the invoking user, and the working directory, so it provides the accountability that a shared root password destroys -- enable <code>Defaults log_input,log_output</code> and sudo can even record a replayable session transcript under <code>/var/log/sudo-io/</code>. Second, the cached credential is per-terminal: after a successful sudo, subsequent commands skip the prompt for <code>timestamp_timeout</code> minutes, and <code>sudo -k</code> clears that cache immediately, which you want at the end of a sensitive task. The most dangerous misconfiguration remains granting a command that can spawn a shell -- editors, pagers, <code>find -exec</code>, language interpreters -- because any of these turns a narrow grant into full root, the basis of countless privilege-escalation findings.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>When a user reports <em>not in the sudoers file, this incident will be reported</em>, the fix is to add them to <strong>wheel</strong> (RHEL) or <strong>sudo</strong> (Debian) with <code>usermod -aG</code>, or add a sudoers rule using <strong>visudo</strong>. Never edit <code>/etc/sudoers</code> directly with vi -- a syntax error there can lock out all administrative access.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[3].push(
  {heading:"File Permissions, Special Bits, and umask", body:"<p>Discretionary access control on Linux begins with the classic permission model: every file and directory has an owner, a group, and a set of read, write, and execute bits for owner, group, and others. This model is so fundamental that nearly every security incident eventually traces back to a permission set incorrectly.</p><h3>Reading rwx</h3><p>Running <code>ls -l</code> shows a ten-character string such as <code>-rwxr-xr--</code>. The first character is the type (<code>-</code> file, <code>d</code> directory, <code>l</code> symlink), then three triads of <span class='keyterm'>rwx</span> for owner, group, and others. <code>r</code> is read, <code>w</code> is write, <code>x</code> is execute. On a directory, <code>x</code> means the ability to <em>enter</em> it (cd into and traverse), and <code>r</code> means the ability to <em>list</em> its contents -- a distinction that surprises many candidates.</p><h3>Octal Versus Symbolic</h3><p>Permissions are set with <code>chmod</code> in either notation. <span class='keyterm'>Octal</span> assigns a digit per triad: read=4, write=2, execute=1, summed. So <code>chmod 750 script.sh</code> means owner rwx (7), group r-x (5), others none (0). <span class='keyterm'>Symbolic</span> notation edits relatively: <code>chmod g+w file</code> adds group write, <code>chmod o-r file</code> removes others' read, <code>chmod u=rwx,go= file</code> sets owner full and clears the rest.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Octal</th><th>Symbolic</th><th>Meaning</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>7</td><td>rwx</td><td>read, write, execute</td></tr><tr><td>6</td><td>rw-</td><td>read, write</td></tr><tr><td>5</td><td>r-x</td><td>read, execute</td></tr><tr><td>4</td><td>r--</td><td>read only</td></tr><tr><td>0</td><td>---</td><td>no access</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Ownership: chown and chgrp</h3><p><code>chown</code> changes the owner and optionally the group: <code>chown alice file</code>, <code>chown alice:devs file</code>, or just the group with <code>chown :devs file</code>. <code>chgrp devs file</code> is the group-only equivalent. Add <code>-R</code> to recurse through a directory tree. Only root may give a file away to another user.</p><h3>The Special Bits: SUID, SGID, Sticky</h3><p>Beyond rwx are three <span class='keyterm'>special permission bits</span>, represented by a leading fourth octal digit. <span class='keyterm'>SUID</span> (4) on an executable makes it run as the file's owner regardless of who launches it -- this is how <code>passwd</code> can update <code>/etc/shadow</code>. It appears as an <code>s</code> in the owner-execute position. <span class='keyterm'>SGID</span> (2) does the same for the group, and on a <em>directory</em> it forces new files to inherit the directory's group -- invaluable for shared project folders. The <span class='keyterm'>sticky bit</span> (1) on a directory (shown as <code>t</code>) restricts deletion so users may only remove their own files; this is why <code>/tmp</code> is world-writable yet safe (mode <code>1777</code>).</p><p>Set them in octal -- <code>chmod 4755 prog</code> for SUID, <code>chmod 2775 shared/</code> for SGID, <code>chmod 1777 /tmp</code> for sticky -- or symbolically with <code>chmod u+s</code>, <code>chmod g+s</code>, <code>chmod +t</code>. Stray SUID-root binaries are a top privilege-escalation risk, so auditors hunt them with <code>find / -perm -4000 -type f</code>.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Special bit</th><th>Octal</th><th>On a file</th><th>On a directory</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>SUID</td><td>4000</td><td>Run as file owner</td><td>(no effect)</td></tr><tr><td>SGID</td><td>2000</td><td>Run as file group</td><td>New files inherit dir group</td></tr><tr><td>Sticky</td><td>1000</td><td>(no effect)</td><td>Only owner may delete own files</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Capital Versus Lowercase in ls</h3><p>The special-bit characters in <code>ls -l</code> carry a subtlety worth memorizing: a lowercase <code>s</code> or <code>t</code> means the execute bit is <em>also</em> set, while an uppercase <code>S</code> or <code>T</code> means the special bit is set but the underlying execute bit is <em>not</em> -- often a misconfiguration. So <code>-rwsr-xr-x</code> is a normal SUID program, but <code>-rwSr--r--</code> is SUID without owner-execute, which usually does nothing useful. When a SUID program mysteriously fails to elevate, this missing execute bit is a prime suspect.</p><p>It is also worth internalizing how permissions are evaluated, because the order is not intuitive: the kernel checks the <em>owner</em> triad if you are the owner, otherwise the <em>group</em> triad if you are in the group, otherwise the <em>other</em> triad -- and it stops at the first matching class. This means a more permissive <em>other</em> setting does not help the owner if the owner triad is restrictive; a file mode <code>604</code> (<code>rw----r--</code>) actually denies the owning group all access while granting everyone else read. The root user bypasses read and write checks entirely but still honors the execute bit, which is why even root cannot run a file that has no <code>x</code> bit anywhere without an explicit interpreter. Directory traversal adds another wrinkle: to reach <code>/a/b/c</code> you need execute on every component directory along the path, regardless of the permissions on <code>c</code> itself.</p><h3>umask and Default Permissions</h3><p>New files do not get rwx for everyone; the <span class='keyterm'>umask</span> subtracts permissions from the base (666 for files, 777 for directories). A umask of <code>022</code> yields <code>644</code> files and <code>755</code> directories -- the common default. A tighter <code>077</code> yields <code>600</code> and <code>700</code>, keeping new files private to the owner. Set it per-session with <code>umask 027</code> or persistently in <code>/etc/profile</code> or a login script.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>Compute umask by subtraction, not bitwise tricks for the exam: files start at 666, directories at 777, then subtract the umask. A umask of 022 gives 644/755. To find risky SUID binaries, the canonical command is <code>find / -perm -4000 -type f 2&gt;/dev/null</code>.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[3].push(
  {heading:"Access Control Lists and File Attributes", body:"<p>The traditional owner/group/other model has a hard limit: a file can only express permissions for one group. When two different groups need different access to the same file, you need <span class='keyterm'>Access Control Lists (ACLs)</span>. Separately, <span class='keyterm'>file attributes</span> control behaviors the permission bits cannot, such as immutability.</p><h3>Viewing and Setting ACLs</h3><p>ACLs extend permissions to multiple named users and groups. View them with <code>getfacl file</code> and set them with <code>setfacl</code>. To grant user <code>bob</code> read and write on a file without touching its owner or group, run <code>setfacl -m u:bob:rw file</code> (the <code>-m</code> modifies). Grant a group with <code>setfacl -m g:auditors:r file</code>. Remove a specific entry with <code>setfacl -x u:bob file</code>, and strip all ACLs with <code>setfacl -b file</code>. When a file carries an ACL, <code>ls -l</code> shows a trailing <code>+</code> after the permission string.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Command</th><th>Purpose</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>getfacl file</code></td><td>Display all ACL entries</td></tr><tr><td><code>setfacl -m u:bob:rw file</code></td><td>Grant bob read/write</td></tr><tr><td><code>setfacl -x u:bob file</code></td><td>Remove bob's entry</td></tr><tr><td><code>setfacl -b file</code></td><td>Remove every ACL</td></tr><tr><td><code>setfacl -d -m u:bob:rwx dir</code></td><td>Set a default ACL on a directory</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Default ACLs and Inheritance</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>default ACL</span> on a directory is inherited by every file and subdirectory created inside it, solving the shared-folder problem cleanly. You set one with the <code>-d</code> flag: <code>setfacl -d -m g:project:rwx /srv/project</code>. New files in that directory automatically receive the group's access without any post-creation step. Recurse an existing tree with <code>setfacl -R -m ...</code>.</p><h3>The ACL Mask</h3><p>Every ACL has a <span class='keyterm'>mask</span> that defines the maximum effective permissions for all named users and the owning group. Even if you grant <code>bob</code> rwx, the mask caps what he actually gets; <code>getfacl</code> annotates each entry with its <em>effective</em> permission when the mask reduces it. Adjust the mask with <code>setfacl -m m::rx file</code>. This is a frequent gotcha: a user has an ACL entry granting write, yet cannot write, because the mask is read-only.</p><h3>File Attributes: chattr and lsattr</h3><p>Beyond permissions, the ext and xfs filesystems support <span class='keyterm'>extended attributes</span> changed with <code>chattr</code> and viewed with <code>lsattr</code>. The two security-critical ones are immutable and append-only.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Attribute</th><th>Flag</th><th>Effect</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Immutable</td><td><code>+i</code></td><td>File cannot be modified, deleted, renamed, or linked -- even by root</td></tr><tr><td>Append-only</td><td><code>+a</code></td><td>File can only be opened for appending; ideal for logs</td></tr></tbody></table><p>Set immutability with <code>chattr +i /etc/resolv.conf</code> to stop a service from overwriting it; remove it with <code>chattr -i</code>. The append-only flag <code>chattr +a /var/log/audit/audit.log</code> protects audit trails from tampering -- an attacker cannot truncate or rewrite the file, only add to it. Verify with <code>lsattr</code>, which prints the flag letters. Because even root must first clear the flag, these attributes are a meaningful defense against accidental or malicious changes.</p><table><thead><tr><th>chattr flag</th><th>Effect</th><th>Typical use</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>+i</code></td><td>Immutable -- no change, delete, rename, link</td><td>Lock critical config files</td></tr><tr><td><code>+a</code></td><td>Append-only</td><td>Tamper-resistant logs</td></tr><tr><td><code>+A</code></td><td>Do not update atime</td><td>Reduce write churn</td></tr><tr><td><code>+s</code></td><td>Secure delete (zero blocks on unlink)</td><td>Sensitive scratch files</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Copying ACLs and Backup Gotchas</h3><p>Two operational pitfalls trip up administrators. First, not every tool preserves ACLs and attributes: <code>cp</code> needs <code>--preserve=all</code> (or <code>-a</code>) and <code>rsync</code> needs <code>-A</code> for ACLs plus <code>-X</code> for extended attributes, or the copy silently drops them. Second, the filesystem must be mounted with ACL support; on older setups the <code>acl</code> mount option in <code>/etc/fstab</code> was required, though modern ext4 and xfs enable it by default. You can clone one file's ACL to another with <code>getfacl src | setfacl --set-file=- dst</code>, which is the clean way to replicate a complex permission set. When an ACL is present but seemingly ineffective, recheck the mask first and the mount options second.</p><p>It is worth being precise about how the mask is recalculated, because it surprises people. Each time you add or modify a named-user or group entry with <code>setfacl -m</code>, the mask is automatically recomputed to the union of those entries unless you set it explicitly in the same command. So granting <code>bob</code> rwx can silently widen the mask and, with it, the effective permissions of every other named entry. To pin the mask and stop that drift, include an explicit <code>m::</code> term, as in <code>setfacl -m u:bob:rwx,m::r-x file</code>. Default ACLs interact with <code>umask</code> too: when a directory carries a default ACL, the umask no longer governs new files there -- the default ACL does -- which is exactly the behavior you want for a shared project tree but a gotcha if you forget it is in place.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>A monitoring agent keeps rewriting <code>/etc/resolv.conf</code> with the wrong nameserver. You set the correct values, then run <code>chattr +i /etc/resolv.conf</code> so even processes running as root cannot overwrite it. To later edit it legitimately you must first <code>chattr -i</code> the file.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[3].push(
  {heading:"SELinux: Contexts, Modes, and Troubleshooting", body:"<p>Standard permissions are <em>discretionary</em> -- the file owner can change them at will. <span class='keyterm'>SELinux</span> (Security-Enhanced Linux) adds a layer of <span class='keyterm'>mandatory access control (MAC)</span> enforced by the kernel according to a system-wide policy that even root cannot casually override. It is the default on the Red Hat family and a guaranteed exam topic.</p><h3>The Three Modes</h3><p>SELinux runs in one of three modes. <span class='keyterm'>Enforcing</span> applies the policy and blocks violations. <span class='keyterm'>Permissive</span> does not block but <em>logs</em> what it would have blocked -- invaluable for troubleshooting. <span class='keyterm'>Disabled</span> turns it off entirely. Check the mode with <code>getenforce</code> and switch live between enforcing and permissive with <code>setenforce 1</code> or <code>setenforce 0</code>. A live switch is temporary; the persistent setting lives in <code>/etc/selinux/config</code> (the <code>SELINUX=</code> line), and moving to or from <em>disabled</em> requires a reboot and filesystem relabel.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Mode</th><th>Behavior</th><th>Set live with</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Enforcing</td><td>Policy enforced, denials blocked and logged</td><td><code>setenforce 1</code></td></tr><tr><td>Permissive</td><td>Denials logged but allowed through</td><td><code>setenforce 0</code></td></tr><tr><td>Disabled</td><td>SELinux off (config + reboot only)</td><td>n/a</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Contexts: The Heart of SELinux</h3><p>Every process and file carries a <span class='keyterm'>security context</span> of the form <code>user:role:type:level</code>, for example <code>system_u:object_r:httpd_sys_content_t:s0</code>. The <em>type</em> is what matters most: policy rules permit a process type (a <em>domain</em>) to act on file types. View contexts with <code>ls -Z</code> for files and <code>ps -Z</code> for processes. The classic failure is a web page in a non-default location whose type is wrong, so <code>httpd_t</code> is denied access even though the Unix permissions are fine.</p><h3>Fixing Contexts: chcon, restorecon, semanage</h3><p>You change a context temporarily with <code>chcon -t httpd_sys_content_t /web/index.html</code>, but a relabel will revert it. The durable fix is two steps: register the correct context in policy with <code>semanage fcontext -a -t httpd_sys_content_t \"/web(/.*)?\"</code>, then apply it with <code>restorecon -Rv /web</code>. <code>restorecon</code> resets files to the context the policy says they should have, which is also the universal repair when contexts get mangled.</p><h3>Booleans</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Booleans</span> are on/off switches that toggle policy behavior without writing custom rules. List them with <code>getsebool -a</code> and set one persistently with <code>setsebool -P httpd_can_network_connect on</code> (the <code>-P</code> makes it survive reboots). For example, allowing Apache to reach a backend database is a single boolean rather than a policy rewrite.</p><h3>Troubleshooting: audit2allow and sealert</h3><p>SELinux denials are logged to <code>/var/log/audit/audit.log</code> as <code>type=AVC</code> messages. When a legitimate action is wrongly denied, you can generate a custom policy module: <code>ausearch -m AVC -ts recent | audit2allow -M mypol</code> creates <code>mypol.pp</code>, which you load with <code>semodule -i mypol.pp</code>. The <code>sealert</code> tool (from setroubleshoot) parses denials into plain-English explanations with suggested fixes. The disciplined workflow is: reproduce in permissive mode, read the AVC, prefer a boolean or correct context over a custom module, and only write a module as a last resort.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Task</th><th>Command</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Show current mode</td><td><code>getenforce</code> / <code>sestatus</code></td></tr><tr><td>View file context</td><td><code>ls -Z file</code></td></tr><tr><td>Temporarily set context</td><td><code>chcon -t type file</code></td></tr><tr><td>Reset to policy default</td><td><code>restorecon -Rv path</code></td></tr><tr><td>Register a permanent context</td><td><code>semanage fcontext -a -t type 'path'</code></td></tr><tr><td>Flip a boolean persistently</td><td><code>setsebool -P name on</code></td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Ports, Logins, and Relabeling</h3><p>SELinux policy governs more than files. To let a daemon bind a non-standard port you must label that port, not just open the firewall: <code>semanage port -a -t http_port_t -p tcp 8443</code> tells policy that 8443 is legitimate web traffic, otherwise <code>httpd_t</code> is denied the bind even though nothing else blocks it. User logins map to SELinux users via <code>semanage login</code>, controlling which roles and domains a Linux account may enter. After a context-wide change -- or when the filesystem was mounted with the wrong labels -- you force a full relabel by creating <code>/.autorelabel</code> and rebooting, or run <code>restorecon -R /</code> on a quiet system. The <code>chcon</code>-versus-<code>semanage fcontext</code> distinction is heavily tested: <code>chcon</code> is a temporary edit that the next relabel erases, while <code>semanage fcontext</code> plus <code>restorecon</code> is the durable, relabel-safe fix.</p><p>Targeted policy is the default and confines only specific high-risk daemons; everything else runs in the unconfined <code>unconfined_t</code> domain, which is why most desktop activity is unaffected while Apache, named, and sshd are tightly boxed. A handful of commands carry most of the diagnostic weight: <code>sestatus</code> shows the mode and the loaded policy in one view, <code>matchpathcon /path</code> prints the context a file <em>should</em> have so you can compare it to what <code>ls -Z</code> reports, and <code>semodule -l</code> lists installed policy modules. When you see <code>type=AVC ... denied { ... }</code> in the audit log, the <code>scontext</code> (source/process) and <code>tcontext</code> (target/file) fields name exactly which domain was denied which type, turning an opaque failure into a precise label mismatch you can fix with a boolean or a context correction.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>If a service works fine after <code>setenforce 0</code> but fails when enforcing, the problem is an SELinux <strong>context</strong> or <strong>boolean</strong>, not a Unix permission. Reach for <code>restorecon</code> to fix mislabeled files and <code>setsebool -P</code> to flip a policy switch -- never disable SELinux as the fix.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[3].push(
  {heading:"AppArmor and Secure Remote Access", body:"<p>SELinux is not the only mandatory access control on Linux. The Debian and SUSE families default to <span class='keyterm'>AppArmor</span>, which is simpler conceptually. This section also covers hardening the single most important remote-access service, SSH, and the safe alternatives to legacy protocols.</p><h3>AppArmor Versus SELinux</h3><p>Where SELinux labels every object with a context, <span class='keyterm'>AppArmor</span> confines programs by <em>path</em>. Each profile in <code>/etc/apparmor.d/</code> lists which files a program may read, write, or execute. Profiles run in <em>enforce</em> mode (violations blocked) or <em>complain</em> mode (violations only logged). You inspect status with <code>aa-status</code>, switch a profile with <code>aa-enforce</code> or <code>aa-complain</code>, and generate one interactively with <code>aa-genprof</code>.</p><p>The path-based model has a practical consequence the exam likes to probe: because AppArmor keys on file paths, moving or hard-linking a confined binary to a different location can escape its profile, whereas SELinux labels follow the inode and so survive a move within the same filesystem. AppArmor profiles can be loaded individually rather than as one monolithic policy, and a profile in complain mode logs would-be denials to the journal so you can refine it with <code>aa-logprof</code> before switching to enforce. Both systems share the same core idea -- confine a trusted program so that even if it is compromised it cannot reach files outside its declared needs -- but they differ in whether that boundary is drawn around a label or around a pathname.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Aspect</th><th>SELinux</th><th>AppArmor</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Model</td><td>Label/context based</td><td>Path based</td></tr><tr><td>Default on</td><td>RHEL, Fedora, CentOS</td><td>Ubuntu, Debian, SUSE</td></tr><tr><td>Modes</td><td>enforcing / permissive / disabled</td><td>enforce / complain</td></tr><tr><td>Key tools</td><td>getenforce, semanage, restorecon</td><td>aa-status, aa-enforce, aa-complain</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Hardening SSHD</h3><p>The OpenSSH server reads <code>/etc/ssh/sshd_config</code>. The most impactful hardening directives are: <code>PermitRootLogin no</code> (force admins to log in as themselves then escalate), <code>PasswordAuthentication no</code> (require keys), <code>PubkeyAuthentication yes</code>, and <code>AllowUsers</code> or <code>AllowGroups</code> to whitelist who may connect. Always validate changes with <code>sshd -t</code> before restarting, and keep a second session open in case you lock yourself out.</p><h3>Key-Based Authentication</h3><p>Replacing passwords with key pairs eliminates the most common attack surface. Generate a modern key with <code>ssh-keygen -t ed25519</code>, copy the public half with <code>ssh-copy-id user@host</code> (which appends it to the remote <code>~/.ssh/authorized_keys</code>), then disable password auth. The private key stays on the client and should be protected with a passphrase. Correct permissions matter: <code>~/.ssh</code> must be <code>700</code> and <code>authorized_keys</code> <code>600</code>, or sshd silently ignores them.</p><h3>SFTP and chroot Jails</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>SFTP</span> tunnels file transfer over the SSH channel, so it inherits SSH's encryption and authentication -- always prefer it to FTP. You can confine SFTP users to a directory tree with <code>ChrootDirectory</code> plus <code>ForceCommand internal-sftp</code> in sshd_config, building a <span class='keyterm'>chroot jail</span> that prevents a user from seeing the wider filesystem.</p><h3>fail2ban</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>fail2ban</span> watches log files for repeated failures and dynamically bans the offending IP via the firewall. Jails are defined in <code>/etc/fail2ban/jail.local</code> with parameters like <code>maxretry</code>, <code>findtime</code>, and <code>bantime</code>. Check active bans with <code>fail2ban-client status sshd</code>. It dramatically reduces brute-force noise against SSH.</p><h3>Avoiding Legacy Protocols and Secure Boot</h3><p>Never run <span class='keyterm'>Telnet</span> (port 23) or plain <span class='keyterm'>TFTP</span>/FTP for administration -- they transmit credentials in cleartext. Replace Telnet with SSH and FTP with SFTP or SCP. At the platform level, <span class='keyterm'>Secure Boot</span> in UEFI verifies the cryptographic signature of the bootloader and kernel, preventing unsigned or tampered boot code from running -- a hardware-rooted defense complementing the OS-level controls above.</p><table><thead><tr><th>sshd_config directive</th><th>Hardening effect</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>PermitRootLogin no</code></td><td>Block direct root login</td></tr><tr><td><code>PasswordAuthentication no</code></td><td>Require key-based auth</td></tr><tr><td><code>AllowGroups sshusers</code></td><td>Whitelist who may connect</td></tr><tr><td><code>MaxAuthTries 3</code></td><td>Limit guesses per connection</td></tr><tr><td><code>Protocol 2</code> / <code>X11Forwarding no</code></td><td>Drop legacy SSHv1, disable X tunneling</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Validating and Recovering SSH Changes</h3><p>Never restart sshd blind. Run <code>sshd -t</code> (or <code>sshd -T</code> to dump the effective config) to catch syntax errors first, then reload while keeping your current session open as a safety net. If a change does lock you out, recovery is through the console or a cloud serial port, not another SSH session. A subtle gotcha is that newer OpenSSH splits config into <code>/etc/ssh/sshd_config.d/*.conf</code> drop-ins that may override the main file -- so a setting that appears correct in <code>sshd_config</code> can be silently overridden, which is exactly why <code>sshd -T</code> (showing the merged result) is the source of truth.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Legacy protocol</th><th>Port</th><th>Secure replacement</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Telnet</td><td>23</td><td>SSH (22)</td></tr><tr><td>FTP</td><td>21</td><td>SFTP / SCP over SSH</td></tr><tr><td>TFTP</td><td>69</td><td>SFTP, or HTTPS for provisioning</td></tr><tr><td>rsh / rlogin</td><td>514 / 513</td><td>SSH</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>Two SSH config lines do the heavy lifting: <code>PermitRootLogin no</code> and <code>PasswordAuthentication no</code>. Pair them with key-based auth and fail2ban. Remember AppArmor is <strong>path-based</strong> (Ubuntu/SUSE) while SELinux is <strong>label-based</strong> (RHEL) -- a common compare-and-contrast question.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[3].push(
  {heading:"Account Hardening and Password Policy", body:"<p>Strong authentication is only as good as the account policy behind it. Hardening accounts means enforcing good passwords, expiring them, limiting reuse, layering on multi-factor authentication, and constraining what compromised accounts can do.</p><h3>Password Aging with chage</h3><p>The <code>chage</code> command manages password aging stored in <code>/etc/shadow</code>. <code>chage -l alice</code> lists current settings; <code>chage -M 90 alice</code> forces expiry every 90 days; <code>chage -m 7 alice</code> sets a minimum age (preventing rapid cycling to defeat history); <code>chage -W 14 alice</code> warns 14 days ahead; and <code>chage -E 2026-12-31 alice</code> sets an account expiration date. System-wide defaults for new users live in <code>/etc/login.defs</code> (<code>PASS_MAX_DAYS</code>, <code>PASS_MIN_DAYS</code>, <code>PASS_WARN_AGE</code>).</p><table><thead><tr><th>Policy</th><th>Where enforced</th><th>Example</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Complexity / length</td><td>pam_pwquality (<code>pwquality.conf</code>)</td><td><code>minlen=14 minclass=3</code></td></tr><tr><td>Reuse / history</td><td>pam_pwhistory</td><td><code>remember=5</code></td></tr><tr><td>Max age / expiry</td><td><code>chage</code> / <code>/etc/login.defs</code></td><td><code>chage -M 90</code></td></tr><tr><td>Lockout</td><td>pam_faillock</td><td><code>deny=5 unlock_time=900</code></td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Complexity, Length, and Reuse</h3><p>As covered under PAM, <span class='keyterm'>pam_pwquality</span> enforces minimum length and character classes when a password is set, and <span class='keyterm'>pam_pwhistory</span> with <code>remember=5</code> blocks reusing the last five passwords (history is kept in <code>/etc/security/opasswd</code>). Current guidance favors longer passphrases over arbitrary complexity, but the exam still tests the classic complexity directives.</p><h3>Multi-Factor Authentication</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>MFA</span> requires a second factor beyond the password. On Linux the common implementation is the <code>pam_google_authenticator</code> (TOTP) module: the user runs <code>google-authenticator</code> to generate a secret and QR code, then a line in the PAM stack such as <code>auth required pam_google_authenticator.so</code> demands a six-digit time-based code. Hardware tokens and smart cards integrate similarly through PAM, making MFA a property of the authentication stack rather than any single application.</p><h3>Restricted Shells</h3><p>Sometimes an account should exist but do almost nothing. A <span class='keyterm'>restricted shell</span> like <code>rbash</code> (invoke bash as <code>rbash</code> or <code>bash -r</code>) blocks changing directories, setting <code>PATH</code>, redirecting output, and running commands by absolute path -- confining the user to a curated set of tools. For accounts that must never log in at all (service accounts), set the shell to <code>/usr/sbin/nologin</code> or <code>/bin/false</code> so authentication is accepted but no interactive session starts.</p><h3>Avoid Running as Root and Banners</h3><p>The principle of least privilege dictates working as an unprivileged user and escalating with sudo only for the specific task. Disabling direct root login (both at the console via <code>/etc/securetty</code> conventions and over SSH via <code>PermitRootLogin no</code>) forces accountable, per-user escalation. Finally, <span class='keyterm'>security banners</span> presented before and after login -- configured in <code>/etc/issue</code> (local), <code>/etc/issue.net</code> (network), and <code>/etc/motd</code> (post-login), with SSH using the <code>Banner</code> directive -- provide legally meaningful warnings to unauthorized users and are a common compliance requirement.</p><table><thead><tr><th>chage flag</th><th>Sets</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>-M</code></td><td>Maximum days before expiry</td></tr><tr><td><code>-m</code></td><td>Minimum days between changes</td></tr><tr><td><code>-W</code></td><td>Warning days before expiry</td></tr><tr><td><code>-E</code></td><td>Absolute account expiration date</td></tr><tr><td><code>-I</code></td><td>Inactive days after expiry before lock</td></tr><tr><td><code>-l</code></td><td>List current aging settings</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Reading and Locking the Shadow File</h3><p>Aging data lives in colon-separated fields of <code>/etc/shadow</code>: the hashed password, last-change day (days since epoch), min, max, warn, inactive, and expire fields. The hash field itself signals state -- a leading <code>!</code> or <code>*</code> means the account is locked or has no usable password. You lock and unlock interactively rather than editing the file: <code>passwd -l alice</code> prepends a <code>!</code> to disable login, <code>passwd -u alice</code> reverses it, and <code>usermod -L</code>/<code>-U</code> do the same. Note that locking the password does not stop key-based SSH login, so a fully disabled account also needs its shell set to <code>nologin</code> and any authorized keys removed. The <code>passwd -S alice</code> command prints a one-line status (locked, password set, aging) that is the fastest way to audit an account.</p><p>Hardening also means understanding how the hash itself is stored. Modern systems use <code>yescrypt</code> or SHA-512 (<code>$6$</code>) with a per-user salt, configured through <code>/etc/login.defs</code> (<code>ENCRYPT_METHOD</code>) and the <code>pam_unix</code> arguments; the salt is what stops two users with the same password sharing a hash and defeats precomputed rainbow tables. When auditing a fleet, watch for accounts with empty password fields (an immediate login bypass), UID 0 accounts other than root (a backdoor disguised as a normal user, found with <code>awk -F: '$3==0' /etc/passwd</code>), and stale accounts whose owners have left. Tying expiry, lockout, and a strong hashing method together is what turns a collection of individual controls into a coherent account-hardening posture.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Account action</th><th>Command</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Lock password login</td><td><code>passwd -l alice</code></td></tr><tr><td>Unlock</td><td><code>passwd -u alice</code></td></tr><tr><td>Show status</td><td><code>passwd -S alice</code></td></tr><tr><td>No interactive shell</td><td><code>usermod -s /usr/sbin/nologin svc</code></td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>Map each policy to its enforcement point: <strong>aging</strong> is <code>chage</code> and <code>/etc/login.defs</code>; <strong>complexity</strong> is pam_pwquality; <strong>history/reuse</strong> is pam_pwhistory; <strong>lockout</strong> is pam_faillock. Service accounts get <code>/usr/sbin/nologin</code>; limited interactive accounts get <code>rbash</code>.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[3].push(
  {heading:"Cryptography I: Data at Rest and Hashing", body:"<p>Encryption protects data the operating system itself cannot see -- a stolen disk or a leaked backup is worthless if its contents are ciphertext. The exam separates cryptography into data at rest (this section) and data in transit (the next), plus the hashing that underpins integrity.</p><h3>LUKS Full-Disk Encryption</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>LUKS</span> (Linux Unified Key Setup), now at version 2, is the standard for encrypting whole block devices. It encrypts the device with a master key, and that master key is itself encrypted by one or more passphrases or key files stored in <em>key slots</em>, so you can change a passphrase without re-encrypting the disk. You manage it with <code>cryptsetup</code>:</p><p><code>cryptsetup luksFormat /dev/sdb1</code> initializes encryption (destroying existing data). <code>cryptsetup luksOpen /dev/sdb1 securedata</code> unlocks it, creating a decrypted mapper device at <code>/dev/mapper/securedata</code> that you then format and mount. <code>cryptsetup luksClose securedata</code> locks it again. Inspect headers with <code>cryptsetup luksDump /dev/sdb1</code> and add a key slot with <code>cryptsetup luksAddKey</code>.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Command</th><th>Action</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>cryptsetup luksFormat /dev/sdb1</code></td><td>Create a new LUKS container</td></tr><tr><td><code>cryptsetup luksOpen /dev/sdb1 name</code></td><td>Unlock to <code>/dev/mapper/name</code></td></tr><tr><td><code>cryptsetup luksClose name</code></td><td>Lock the device</td></tr><tr><td><code>cryptsetup luksAddKey /dev/sdb1</code></td><td>Add a passphrase to a free key slot</td></tr></tbody></table><p>For automatic mounting at boot, the device is listed in <code>/etc/crypttab</code> (mapping name to device and key source) and the resulting mapper device in <code>/etc/fstab</code>.</p><h3>File-Level Encryption with GPG</h3><p>When you need to encrypt individual files rather than a whole disk, <span class='keyterm'>GPG</span> (GNU Privacy Guard) is the tool. Symmetric encryption with a passphrase uses <code>gpg -c secret.txt</code>, producing <code>secret.txt.gpg</code> that <code>gpg -d secret.txt.gpg</code> decrypts. Asymmetric (public-key) encryption uses <code>gpg -e -r alice@example.com file</code>, which only Alice's private key can open. GPG also signs files for authenticity, combining confidentiality and integrity.</p><h3>Hashing and Integrity</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>cryptographic hash</span> is a one-way fingerprint: any change to the input produces a wildly different output, so hashes verify integrity. Compute them with <code>sha256sum file</code>, <code>sha512sum file</code>, or the older <code>md5sum file</code> (now considered broken for security but still seen for non-adversarial checksums). To verify a download, run <code>sha256sum -c checksums.txt</code>, which recomputes and compares against published values.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Algorithm</th><th>Status</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>MD5</td><td>Broken (collisions); checksum use only</td></tr><tr><td>SHA-1</td><td>Deprecated; avoid for security</td></tr><tr><td>SHA-256 / SHA-512</td><td>Current standard for integrity</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>HMAC</h3><p>A plain hash proves the data is unchanged but not <em>who</em> produced it. An <span class='keyterm'>HMAC</span> (Hash-based Message Authentication Code) mixes a secret key into the hash, so only someone with the key can produce or verify it, giving both integrity and authenticity. HMACs underpin TLS, API signing, and many file-integrity tools.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Goal</th><th>Primitive</th><th>Tool</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Confidentiality (disk)</td><td>Symmetric, master key in slots</td><td>LUKS / <code>cryptsetup</code></td></tr><tr><td>Confidentiality (file)</td><td>Symmetric or public-key</td><td>GPG</td></tr><tr><td>Integrity</td><td>One-way hash</td><td><code>sha256sum</code></td></tr><tr><td>Integrity + authenticity</td><td>Keyed hash</td><td>HMAC</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>GPG Key Management</h3><p>Asymmetric GPG depends on a keyring you actually manage. You create a key pair with <code>gpg --full-generate-key</code>, list public keys with <code>gpg --list-keys</code> and private keys with <code>gpg --list-secret-keys</code>, and share your public key via <code>gpg --export -a alice@example.com</code>. Before encrypting to someone you import and verify their key, because trusting the wrong key undermines the whole scheme. A signed file is verified with <code>gpg --verify file.sig</code>, which is exactly how package managers and release artifacts prove authorship. Two common mistakes: encrypting to your own key only (then no one else can read it), and forgetting that symmetric <code>gpg -c</code> protects with a passphrase that must be transmitted out-of-band.</p><h3>The crypttab and fstab Pairing</h3><p>For LUKS volumes that must mount at boot, <code>/etc/crypttab</code> names the mapper device, the backing block device, and a key source (a passphrase prompt, a key file, or <code>none</code> to prompt interactively). The decrypted <code>/dev/mapper/</code> name then appears in <code>/etc/fstab</code> with its mount point. Get the dependency backwards -- listing the raw device in fstab instead of the mapper name -- and the boot stalls because the encrypted device cannot be mounted directly. A key file referenced from crypttab must itself be tightly permissioned (mode <code>0400</code>, root-owned) or it becomes the weakest link.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>For full-disk encryption the answer is <strong>LUKS</strong> via <code>cryptsetup</code> with a <code>/dev/mapper/</code> device; for individual files it is <strong>GPG</strong>. Hashing (<code>sha256sum</code>) provides integrity only; an <strong>HMAC</strong> adds authenticity by keying the hash. Never cite MD5 or SHA-1 as a secure choice.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[3].push(
  {heading:"Cryptography II: Data in Transit and PKI", body:"<p>Data crossing a network must be protected from eavesdropping and tampering. The dominant mechanism is <span class='keyterm'>TLS</span>, supported by a public-key infrastructure of certificates, with <span class='keyterm'>OpenSSL</span> as the universal toolkit and <span class='keyterm'>WireGuard</span> as a modern VPN.</p><h3>TLS Fundamentals</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>TLS</span> (Transport Layer Security), the successor to SSL, secures connections by combining asymmetric cryptography for the handshake and key exchange with fast symmetric encryption for the bulk data. During the handshake the server presents an X.509 certificate; the client verifies the certificate chains to a trusted <span class='keyterm'>Certificate Authority (CA)</span>, then both sides derive a shared session key. Use modern TLS 1.2 or 1.3 and retire SSLv3 and TLS 1.0/1.1, which are insecure.</p><h3>OpenSSL: Keys, CSRs, and Certificates</h3><p>The <code>openssl</code> command is the Swiss Army knife of TLS. The typical certificate workflow is three steps:</p><ul><li>Generate a private key: <code>openssl genrsa -out server.key 4096</code> (or an EC key with <code>openssl ecparam -genkey</code>).</li><li>Create a <span class='keyterm'>CSR</span> (Certificate Signing Request) to send to a CA: <code>openssl req -new -key server.key -out server.csr</code>, answering prompts for the Common Name and organization.</li><li>Receive the signed certificate from the CA, or for testing generate a self-signed one: <code>openssl req -x509 -newkey rsa:4096 -keyout server.key -out server.crt -days 365 -nodes</code>.</li></ul><table><thead><tr><th>Command</th><th>Purpose</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>openssl genrsa -out k.key 4096</code></td><td>Generate a private key</td></tr><tr><td><code>openssl req -new -key k.key -out k.csr</code></td><td>Create a CSR</td></tr><tr><td><code>openssl x509 -in k.crt -text -noout</code></td><td>Inspect a certificate's fields</td></tr><tr><td><code>openssl s_client -connect host:443</code></td><td>Test a live TLS endpoint</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Inspecting and Testing Certificates</h3><p>To read a certificate's subject, issuer, validity dates, and extensions, run <code>openssl x509 -in server.crt -text -noout</code>. To debug a live service -- view the presented chain, the negotiated protocol, and the cipher -- use <code>openssl s_client -connect www.example.com:443 -servername www.example.com</code>. This is the go-to command when a browser reports a certificate error and you need ground truth.</p><h3>PKI and Certificate Management</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>PKI</span> (Public Key Infrastructure) is the hierarchy of trust: a root CA signs intermediate CAs, which sign end-entity certificates. Trust on a Linux host derives from the system trust store -- the bundle in <code>/etc/pki/tls/certs/</code> (RHEL) or <code>/etc/ssl/certs/</code> (Debian). To trust an internal CA you drop its certificate into <code>/etc/pki/ca-trust/source/anchors/</code> and run <code>update-ca-trust</code> (or <code>/usr/local/share/ca-certificates/</code> plus <code>update-ca-certificates</code> on Debian). Certificates expire, so management means tracking validity dates and renewing before they lapse -- expired certificates are a leading cause of outages.</p><h3>WireGuard</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>WireGuard</span> is a modern, fast VPN built into the kernel. Each peer has a key pair; you generate them with <code>wg genkey</code> piped to <code>wg pubkey</code>, configure interfaces in <code>/etc/wireguard/wg0.conf</code> with each peer's public key and allowed IPs, and bring the tunnel up with <code>wg-quick up wg0</code>. Its small codebase and modern cryptography make it simpler and faster than IPsec or OpenVPN.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Artifact</th><th>Extension</th><th>Holds</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Private key</td><td><code>.key</code></td><td>Secret half -- never share</td></tr><tr><td>CSR</td><td><code>.csr</code></td><td>Public key + identity, sent to CA</td></tr><tr><td>Certificate</td><td><code>.crt</code> / <code>.pem</code></td><td>CA-signed public identity</td></tr><tr><td>PKCS#12 bundle</td><td><code>.p12</code> / <code>.pfx</code></td><td>Key + cert + chain in one file</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Encodings and Conversions</h3><p>Certificates come in two encodings that trip people up: <span class='keyterm'>PEM</span> is Base64 text wrapped in <code>-----BEGIN CERTIFICATE-----</code> markers, while <span class='keyterm'>DER</span> is the same data in raw binary. Many Windows and Java tools expect DER or a PKCS#12 bundle, so conversion is routine: <code>openssl x509 -in cert.pem -outform der -out cert.der</code> and <code>openssl pkcs12 -export -in cert.pem -inkey server.key -out bundle.p12</code>. When a service rejects a certificate that looks valid, a format mismatch is a common cause. You can also verify that a key and certificate actually pair by comparing their moduli: <code>openssl x509 -noout -modulus -in cert.pem | sha256sum</code> versus the same against the key.</p><h3>Revocation and Expiry</h3><p>Trust is not only about signing; it must be revocable. A <span class='keyterm'>CRL</span> (Certificate Revocation List) and the online <span class='keyterm'>OCSP</span> protocol let clients check whether a still-dated certificate has been pulled -- after a key compromise, for example. In day-to-day operations, expiry is the bigger killer: an unrenewed certificate takes a service down at midnight on its <code>notAfter</code> date. Automated issuance with ACME clients like <code>certbot</code> renews Let's Encrypt certificates before they lapse, which is why scripted renewal plus monitoring of the validity window is the standard production answer.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>Know the OpenSSL trio: <code>genrsa</code> (key), <code>req</code> (CSR or self-signed cert), and <code>s_client -connect</code> (test). <strong>Self-signed certificates are fine for testing but must not be used in production</strong> -- they break the chain of trust and train users to ignore warnings. Use a real CA, or an internal CA added to the trust store with <code>update-ca-trust</code>.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[3].push(
  {heading:"Compliance, Auditing, and File Integrity", body:"<p>The final security topic is verifying that a system stays in a known-good, compliant state over time. This spans vulnerability scanning, automated compliance checks, file-integrity monitoring, secure data destruction, and the integrity of the software supply chain.</p><h3>Vulnerability Scanning and CVEs</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>CVE</span> (Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures) is a unique identifier for a publicly known flaw, such as <code>CVE-2021-44228</code> (Log4Shell). Keeping packages patched closes CVEs; <code>dnf updateinfo list security</code> or <code>apt list --upgradable</code> reveals pending security updates. To discover what is exposed on the network, <span class='keyterm'>nmap</span> is the standard scanner: <code>nmap -sV 10.0.0.0/24</code> enumerates open ports and service versions, and <code>nmap -sS -p- host</code> performs a full TCP SYN scan. Cross-referencing discovered service versions against CVE databases is the core of vulnerability assessment.</p><h3>OpenSCAP and Compliance Benchmarks</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>OpenSCAP</span> automates compliance auditing against standardized policies (SCAP content) such as CIS Benchmarks, DISA STIGs, and PCI-DSS profiles. The <code>oscap</code> tool scans a host and produces a pass/fail report: <code>oscap xccdf eval --profile xccdf_org.ssgproject.content_profile_cis --results scan.xml --report report.html /usr/share/xml/scap/ssg/content/ssg-rhel9-ds.xml</code>. The HTML report flags each failed control with a remediation. It is the tool of choice when a question mentions automated STIG or CIS compliance.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Tool</th><th>Security role</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>nmap</code></td><td>Network/port and service-version scanning</td></tr><tr><td><code>oscap</code> (OpenSCAP)</td><td>Automated compliance benchmark evaluation</td></tr><tr><td>AIDE</td><td>File-integrity baseline and change detection</td></tr><tr><td><code>rkhunter</code> / <code>chkrootkit</code></td><td>Rootkit and backdoor detection</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>File Integrity Monitoring</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>AIDE</span> (Advanced Intrusion Detection Environment) builds a cryptographic baseline of critical files -- hashes, permissions, ownership, timestamps -- stored in a database. After installing, you initialize the baseline with <code>aide --init</code>, move the database into place, and later run <code>aide --check</code> to report any drift. Because an attacker who modifies a system binary or config file changes its hash, AIDE detects tampering that permissions alone would miss. <span class='keyterm'>rkhunter</span> and <code>chkrootkit</code> complement it by scanning specifically for known rootkit signatures and suspicious system changes.</p><h3>Secure Data Destruction</h3><p>Deleting a file merely unlinks it; the data persists until overwritten. Secure destruction overwrites the bytes. <code>shred -vfz -n 3 /dev/sdb</code> overwrites a device three times then zeros it. <code>dd if=/dev/urandom of=/dev/sdb bs=1M</code> fills a disk with random data. <code>badblocks -w /dev/sdb</code> performs a destructive write test that also wipes. For self-encrypting or LUKS disks, a <span class='keyterm'>cryptographic erase</span> -- destroying the encryption key -- instantly renders all data unrecoverable, the fastest method for large drives. Note that on SSDs, wear-leveling can leave residual data, so the ATA secure-erase command or cryptographic erase is preferred over overwriting.</p><h3>Software Supply Chain</h3><p>Integrity extends to the software you install. Packages are cryptographically signed, and tools verify the signature against trusted GPG keys before installing -- <code>rpm --checksig package.rpm</code> or <code>dnf</code>'s automatic <code>gpgcheck=1</code> in repo files, and <code>apt</code>'s signed <code>Release</code> files. Only install from trusted, signed repositories, verify download checksums, and keep signing keys current to defend against tampered or malicious packages.</p><table><thead><tr><th>nmap scan</th><th>What it does</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>-sS</code></td><td>Stealth TCP SYN scan (default, needs root)</td></tr><tr><td><code>-sV</code></td><td>Probe service and version banners</td></tr><tr><td><code>-O</code></td><td>OS fingerprinting</td></tr><tr><td><code>-p-</code></td><td>All 65535 ports</td></tr><tr><td><code>-sn</code></td><td>Ping sweep, host discovery only</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Destruction Method by Media</h3><p>The right wipe depends on the medium. Multi-pass overwrite (<code>shred</code>, <code>badblocks -w</code>) suits magnetic hard disks, where each pass physically rewrites the platter. On SSDs and NVMe, wear-leveling silently remaps blocks so overwrites may miss the real data; there the ATA <em>secure erase</em> command (<code>hdparm --security-erase</code>) or <code>nvme format --ses=1</code> issues a controller-level purge instead. For any LUKS or self-encrypting drive, a <span class='keyterm'>cryptographic erase</span> -- destroying the key with <code>cryptsetup luksErase</code> -- is instant and complete regardless of capacity, because the ciphertext becomes meaningless. Physical destruction (shredding, degaussing) remains the standard for the highest classifications.</p><p>Compliance is also a lifecycle, not a one-time scan. After an OpenSCAP evaluation flags failed controls, the same SCAP content can generate a remediation script or an Ansible playbook to bring the host into line, after which you rescan to prove closure -- the scan/remediate/rescan loop auditors expect to see. AIDE fits the same discipline: its baseline must be regenerated and re-secured after every legitimate patch cycle, or routine updates drown real tampering in false positives, and the database itself should be stored offline so an attacker cannot rewrite it to match their changes. Throughout, the supply-chain controls -- signed repositories, verified checksums, and current GPG keys -- ensure that the known-good state you are measuring against was itself built from trustworthy bits.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Media</th><th>Preferred method</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Magnetic HDD</td><td><code>shred</code> / <code>badblocks -w</code> overwrite</td></tr><tr><td>SSD / NVMe</td><td>ATA secure erase / <code>nvme format</code></td></tr><tr><td>Encrypted (LUKS/SED)</td><td>Cryptographic erase (destroy key)</td></tr><tr><td>Highest classification</td><td>Physical destruction / degauss</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>Match the tool to the task: <strong>nmap</strong> finds open services, <strong>OpenSCAP/oscap</strong> audits against CIS/STIG benchmarks, <strong>AIDE</strong> detects file tampering via hash baselines, and <strong>rkhunter</strong> hunts rootkits. For wiping, <code>shred</code> and <code>badblocks -w</code> overwrite, while <strong>cryptographic erase</strong> (destroy the key) is fastest for encrypted media.</div>"}
);
